Sep 29 2009 	Good value with decent location	The cheap price ($40) was the incitive to stay here on our 2 day trip through Vegas on our way to the Grand Canyon. After coming to the conclusion that it was just a place to sleep we booked this hotel instead of paying close to $100 for a better hotel. The location isn't in the center of the strip but that was fine with us since we had a rental car and could drive to the other parts of the strip easily.Checkin took less than 2 minutes but we didn't check in until 11pm so that probably had something to do with it, but it was very easy and the front desk was friendly. I already knew about the $8 per day hotel fee that isn't included in the initial room price so just be aware of that but my understanding is that all the hotels have some kind of 'daily use' fee and $8 wasn't too bad.The hotel is definitely dated but so are all the other discount hotels on the strip. Our room was a little cheesey with mirrors on the ceiling but it was clean and surprisingly quiet with it pretty much being right next to the airport. But it did start to smell like smoke the second day even though we were on a no smoking floor. I guess someone didn't follow that rule. We never once woke up to a plane during the night. The pool area was a nice getaway for the casino with lots of water features and a tropical environment. It's a great place to hang out, especially the swim up bar.We didn't gamble at the hotel but it stayed pretty busy. I will say it seemed like 90% of the guests were over 50 and with us being in our 20s it wasn't really the place to hang out and gamble but we just went across the street to the NY hotel and had fun over there. Overall if you're just looking for a place to sleep stay at the Tropicana and go have fun at some of the other hotels. I really enjoyed the pub bar at the NY hotel and also the dueling piano bar there as well. There's plenty to see and do in the nicer casinos but for the price you can't beat the Tropicana. We never ate at the hotel so I don't know how the food is, they definitely don't as many options as the larger hotels, but again, it's an easy walk to several hotels from the Tropicana.	
