Apr 30 2009 	Great Experience for the Money	I want to give a good perspective of the good and bad of staying at the Tropicana, as I was very concerned after reading the reviews online. Overall, I had a great experience, but you have to know what to expect. I had a Garden room overlooking the gardens and pool area, on the second floor (two beds, non smoking):Positives:1) Gardens, Pool and gym are beautiful and well maintained.2) I found the staff to be friendly and helpful. In the casino, the dealers were experienced and friendly and you can generally find low limit tables ($5).3) The café was great, the buffet was not (go across to Excaliber from 2-6pm for 2 for 1 dinner buffet - very good and about $18 for two for dinner)4) Location is super – right on the “4 square” with MGM, New York, Excaliber, and right by Monte Carlo, Hooters, Luxor, Mandalay Bay. 5) The cost was superior to any other room I could find online for a similar property.6) Frankly, I preferred the garden room to the Paradise/Island tower. I liked having the small balcony and a shorter walk from the casino to the room (vs the tower).Negative:1) The hotel needs updating – the carpet and wallpaper are old and worn..not a luxury experience by any means, but we only wanted a clean room, bed, towels. All OK. It has a hair dryer, shampoo, soap, TV, alarm clock - basic stuff.2) Sink drained slow, but was fixed on day 2 without asking (housekeeping?)3) I could smell smoke in my non-smoking room, but I think there is a central air conditioning system for all rooms and casino. The smoky smell went away when I turned off / down the air conditioning.4) It seemed there was a communication problem between departments in the hotel -- Security knew my in room safe was out of order (my room number was on their list, and did not plan to replace it, but the front desk didn’t know about the safe and used the room anyway; Security told me the front desk offered a safe deposit box for my laptop, the front desk said security didn’t know they no longer had large boxes, and I had to check it at the bell desk (which made me uncomfortable checking my laptop with the bell desk, but I checked it for my entire stay without any incident ! - great!).	
Apr 29 2009 	Loved the 24 hour pools other things could be worked on	I went to Vegas with friends for a weekend. We're in our mid to late 20s. We don't really gamble. We were looking for a place that had a good pool, where we could basically just sleep/have some drinks, and was a good value. I think that the Tropicana met those criteria.The Good: We loved the 24-hour pools. I can't believe this isn't mentioned more in other reviews. Some of the pools and Jacuzzis are open all night. All night! We probably used them at least 6 times over our 2-night stay. Not crowded at all (maybe people don't know about it...the adult swim pool has a sign that says it is open from 9am-7pm but it's wrong, it's all night...we asked the people that worked there...the 2 Jacuzzis don't have signs and they are 24 hours too...only the main pool closes at 7pm). Come back at 5am and head to the pool! That's what we did. Nice after a night out. I don't know of any/many other hotels in Vegas that have 24-hour pools. Loved the daytime main pool too, which we used all day. The crowd by the pools seemed mostly our age so that was fun. Very few kids. Everyone was friendly and having a good time. Loved having our own drinks there but there were also servers coming around for drink orders. The security at the hotel were super nice, cool guys. I mean, when was the last time someone commented on how cool security was?!? Some couple showed up later and tried to get the security to kick us out for no reason other than to have the Jacuzzi to themselves. It's a hotel Jacuzzi and we were there first! Security actually told US what the couple tried to do and of course, we were not kicked out since we weren't doing anything wrong. One other time, we thought maybe we were being too loud but the security just came over to make sure that we didn't run around the pool and hurt ourselves. Thank you cool security!The No-So-Good: Our room could have been cleaned a little better after our first night. The beds were made and we got new towels but not much else was cleaned in the bathroom. Overall, the hotel and rooms are a bit run down and dated, so we weren't sure about it at first but we got used to it. It is one of the older hotels on the Strip though. Seriously, we were mostly looking for something basic. We weren't planning to spend many waking hours in the room. The Garden Cafe was decent but we had to wait awhile (about 20 minutes) to be seated for lunch and there were only 5 people ahead of us. The Island Buffet was not very good (desserts were cute though) but there was no wait.The Bad: We were booked off an internet website for a non-smoking room in the Paradise Tower (more expensive) with a strip view. When we got there, we were told that the entire Paradise Tower was closed as of the previous day for water and electrical problems...seems like some other reviews here were told they were being refurbished? Not sure what the truth was. No offer to upgrade, no discount, not anything. I was able to request and still get a Strip view but it was a smoking room in the Island Tower, which was supposedly the only thing they had. We took it. I guess we valued the view more than our air quality. After calling the internet website, they were able refund me and give us the Island Tower rate but it was still irritating that I had to spend time out of my trip to make the calls to get it fixed and still take a smoking room. I think Tropicana should have offered some discount right off the bat or upgraded us. They offered us a non-smoking room for the next night but who wants to move after you've already settled in? Well I guess some people do, as I found out that some people we met at the hotel were upgraded to a suite on the 21st floor the next day. Oh well. Also, make sure you know there is a daily resort fee to pay upon check-in. In spite of all that, the weekend was so much fun. It didn't start off great but once we got the initial problems taken care of, all within an hour of our arrival, it was one of the best weekends ever. The hotel was old and the rooms were basic but we are pretty flexible people so we didn't let it ruin our weekend. We can't get over the 24-hour pools! I'm sure we'll be back again.	
Apr 29 2009	BED BUGS	Having worked in the hotel business for 16 years, I inspect every room I stay in. Not necessarily white glove treatment, but through enough to get the items that should be of real concern. Upon check-in at Tropicana and before bringing the luggage to the room, I searched the room - 5242 - for bed bugs. After pulling back the covers on the second bed, we found a fat juicy one crawling on the sheet. He had recently been feeding as you could see the blood through his transparent exoskeleton. I gathered it up took it to the front desk. My goal was not to cause a scene, but rather inform them of the problem and get into a room with no history of problems. The first clerk directed me to the Manager On Duty desk. The supervisor acted like I was a nuisance and immediately referred the manager - she made no eye contact. The manger came and I explained what I found. Before letting me finish, he pulled out what was obviously his usual rhetoric, &quot;All hotels have this problem.&quot; I explained I worked in the hotel business for 16 years and knew it could affect even the best of hotels. However, not all. I explained I wasn't looking for &quot;something for nothing&quot;. I just wanted a room that doesn't get rented out to tours and hasn't had any past problems. He explained he could refund our first night's deposit and allow us to go elsewhere. I explained I knew they kept logs and to find a room with no problems. He explained their bed bug procedures, but I had to interrupt a few times to explain I knew the process and that I just wanted a guarantee of a trouble-free room. He then said they were soldout - on a Sunday that offered very lower than weekend rates? - and all of their suites went to an in-house tournament. He also explained the other tower he could put in hadn't had problems in a while, which he said was &quot;a couple of months ago.&quot; I had to interrupt him again to get him to listen to my simple request. Finally, he went to speak with Housekeeping about a possible room. While waiting for him to return, the supervisor rudely asked us to step aside away from the counter. Is her firmness and lack of personality a line of defense between guest and management? Supervisors like that often make matters worse. However, it's possible because it's a destination resort, repeat business is neither priority nor expected.The manager returned and finally got us a room. We went up to the room and I repeated the inspection. I noticed he had given us a better room (not an upgrade) with a nice view, but it was not necessarily what I wanted. Not seeing any obvious signs of bed bugs, we decided to keep the room. However, on my way home, I found a red splotchy mark on left leg. It looks like I was bit by something. Now I am worried. I sprayed the car trunk and washed all of my clothes in very hot water and bleach. I was a little taken back by the manager dealing with the situation. He anticipated every word out of my mouth and offered his standard defenses prior to me finishing my sentences. He assumed I was guest who was in it for a war of words for a free room. However, had he listened, he could have saved us both time. His lack of ability to deal with a guest &quot;conflict&quot; and the rudeness of the supervisor was cause for my terrible service rating. Having been a Front Office Manager myself for 5 years, I understand some of the avoidant behavior of some desk clerks. However, I don't expect this from the manager. A lack of experience and/or the policies of upper management are usually to blame. Advice: Less fight and more listening. And next time, apologize. No one apologized for our problem or offered sympathies. As far as cleaniness, I realize a bed bug problem is not the fault of housekeeping. These critters travel with guests. However, the sheets on one of the beds had what looked like dry boogers, pubic hairs, and were wrinkled in such a way that would only indicate they had been slept in. I changed the sheets myself. I stayed here for a week in early 2001. It was run down then and the rooms looked like they hadn't been remodeled in years then. Our original room was extremely worn. The second room only had new soft goods (e.g. bedspreads, carpet, curtains). The furniture was worn. In the morning, we could smell cigarette smoke coming from the adjoining room through the adjoining door. I had trouble breathing as a result. We checked out as quickly as possible. To keep a long story short, I had a problem with a guy following us after coming downstairs. He followed us all the way over MGM when I forced him to take the escalator down ahead of us. We backtracked and lost him. He was likely after my sister's wallet as it was exposed in her open purse when he originally passed us going in the opposite direction. MGM security didn't seem too concerned. However, when we got back to to Tropicana and reported it, the security guard we spoke with showed concern and said he would report it. Whether he did or not, I don't know. Be alert in Vegas. Watch out for bed bugs and pickpockets. A little note: I noticed someone earlier noted plastic covers on the mattresses. They are likely bed bug covers and they're not very effective from what I've read. Removing them could not have helped. You may have brought bed bugs home. Another person mentioned the vendors in the long hallway being harassing. We found this true for two of the booths. It felt like we walking through a used car dealership every time we were coming or going from our room.	
