Mar 6 2009 	Not Worth it...	So, I recently finished my 5 week stay at the Tropicana and wanted to give my full review. I lived in a room on the 17th floor facing the MGM. The veiw was not as good as my friends room facing the Excalibur, but it was not a big deal. The only annoying thing were the bright lights. The curtains did not fully black out the room. But, this might be the case for all the hotels on the strip. The rooms themselves are a bit dated. The furniture was kind of mismatched, and the carpeting was a little grungy (I wore my flip flops in the room). The bathrooms could use an update, it never looked bright or clean, probably because it was so old. Also, they use flourescent lights over the mirror which is never flattering. I didn't know anyone who stayed in the garden rooms, but these are supposedly worse. The house keeping staff did their best, though. And were always friendly.The casino area was kind of depressed. The clientale were not the same you would find in say the Bellagio or the Wynn, it almost had a &quot;Fremont&quot; feel to it. There was live music every night in the lounge which people seemed to enjoy. The Comedy Stop was excellent, and I heard the Folies Bergere was a great old Vegas show. Too bad it's last show is coming up this month. I hope to see it before I leave town. The dining experience was sub par some of the other hotels in the same area (I ate at MGM, Mandala Bay, NY NY). The buffet was adequate. I only had breakfast there once, and the omelette guy knew his way around a skillet. I ate a few times at the 24 hour restaraunt. They are in the middle of a remodel, which is a good idea. My husband and I were commenting on how tacky the decor was, and the next week it was closed off and they moved it into the Italian place. I can not know for sure, but I think I got food poisoning here. I ordered a turkey sandwhich with mayo (which I usually never eat) and that night I got really sick and couldn't eat for a week. I did use the gym here, and I'm glad it was included in the room price. It is small, three treadmills, two elipiticals, and a few weight machines. The womens' spa area is nice. They have a hot tub, steam room, and sauna. They have a massuese and different beauty treatments, and a tanning bed. Nothing elaborate. They do offer wi-fi in the room, but you have pay a rediculous fee per day. Overall, for a little more money, I think you could find a better place to stay. I heard the owners are going to start a complete remodel, and they seemed to be starting it while we were there. However, the funny thing is, they are not changing anything. They repainted the hallways...a really unattractive peach and brown. They are re-carpeting the lobby...with the same carpet! So, it might look a little less run down but will not help to refresh the face of the Tropicana. Which is really too bad, because the Trop is in a great location and could benefit from a new look.	
