Jan 14 2009 	The Trop - Lots of fun in Vegas	My wife and I attended the AVN Expo and found the uptown prices pretty steep especially since the CES was on at the same time. I was a bit apprehensive about staying at an older property but my fears never came true. The room was spacious and the bed was very comfortable. The TV was old but worked fine. I did not miss a fancy flat screen since we were out of the room except for sleeping. The shower had plenty of hot water and the tub was big enough for two. The view was of the MGM and New York from our Island tower room.The best part was the friendly staff and the promotions. We did a bit of gambling and before long we received comps for the shows (Follies and Magic), breakfast and dinner.The location is great since it is near the train (east strip) and the tram (west strip). It was easy to get to the Sands Expo although a bit of walking is required.The only negatives was the high cost of Internet ($12 per day) and constant harassment to tour Tahiti Village. After a while they got to know us and just smiled as we walked by.This is a 24 hour property with a small convenience store and three restaurants. Great choice for a few days in Vegas.	
Jan 12 2009 	Tropican...perfect on a budget!!!	I know this place isn't luxurious, it needs a facelift and well, it just stuck in the past. The thing is, I spent most of my time out and about...a fancy room is lost on me. Sure it's nice, but if I can pay a 1/3 of the price as some of the pricier hotels on the strip that's all the more money for me to spend while in town.Admitedly, I was there for a bachelor party, sharing a room with a friend. So for $150 a piece we had a clean, centraly located room on the strip for our 3 nights in Vegas...can't go wrong with that. To put it in perspective, a member of the bachelor party crew stayed at the Wynn instead of the Tropicana. I came in at 11AM and was immediately given a room. He tried to check into the Wynn at 2:30 and they didn't have a room for him till almost 9PM at night! So, you get what you pay for...a Best Western style room with PLENTY of square footage. I would reccomend staying in the Paradise Tower. From what I've read these are the nicer rooms, they're closer to the lobby and have great views. This is where I stayed.Additionaly, skip the booking sites and get them to match their price. You'll avoid the &quot;Resort Fee&quot; and you'll only have to pay for 1 night up front.I'll be back...provided this hotel's still there next time I'm through.	
