Dec 30 2008 	You really get what you pay for...	If you're going to stay at the Trop I would reccomend booking a tower room - they are much newer and nicer, the original part of this hotel is where we were put was built in the mid 1950's and still stands as the original motel style base for the two towers. These rooms are dated and expect them to be well worn however I was surprised our beds were new. The hallways were often seen with glassware and plates in the hall that would be there all day and we were pestered a few times by the cleaning staff asking when we were leaving...this happend on only day 2 of 6. The pool was nice, dated but well maintained with lush tropical style gardens. The food was satisfactory despite a very dated decor and furniture, we maily only stayed at Trop for breakfast as there are much better options a short walk away - but stay away from Hooters next door - it was not consistent with the other ones I've visited, yuck. The staff was very friendly and often eager to help suggest nightlife or dinning. Many of the hotels in the states right now are suffering due to the poor economy and the Trop in Atlantic City just filed under chapter 11. I would reccomend looking into other hotels that are only slightly more expensive; Ballys (better location and cleaner) or even Luxor (clean, more modern) but if cost is a factor the Trop is cheap and in a good location (right across from MGM). If you're a couple guys in your mid 20's like us (first time to Vegas) its a cheap and effective place to stay, we spent very little time in the room aside from when sleeping\recovering however it is unlikely I will return - sorry Tropicana!	
