Nov 14 2008 	Don't Give Up On The Ole Gal Yet	We were enticed to make a last-minute trip by an email from the Tropicana offering $37/night midweek. Reading the reviews, I knew this rate was for the dreaded Garden Rooms, which should be avoided by most. So we booked two nights and arrived at the front desk all smiles and politeness. We talked them down from $30 to $20/night upgrade for the Paradise Tower rooms, although after reading some reviews I realize we might have tried harder for a cheaper or even free upgrade. But no matter because it was SO worth it to upgrade to the Paradise Tower. The elevators are right by the front doors and they are fast. Our 17th-floor room looked fairly upgraded and had new sheets, fluffy towels, a brand-new bedspread, and a rarity in Vegas: a mini fridge! I've paid $10 a night to have a mini fridge in much more expensive hotels in Vegas. Yeah, the decor is a little cheesy and the TV is tiny but that's so VEGAS! Anyway, our room was very clean - so clean that the carpet was still a bit damp from being shampooed. OK, that's not a plus, but we gave them a pass since we weren't originally booked into this room, and the carpet was completely dry -and so clean and fresh! - after we returned from dinner a short while later. We didn't need to call for a big fan or anything.The view of the Strip from our room was awesome, although that mega monstrosity being built across the street next to Monte Carlo saddens me. Looks like it's going to impact views up and down the entire Strip. Still, the rooms facing North have a good view of the Strip, at least in this tower. We found all of the staff to be very friendly and helpful. I did not find the casino to be too smoky at all, and I'm sensitive, but again we were there midweek. I had a wonderful time playing craps (and winning!) with some great characters and nice employees. There was a good band in the lounge. I did notice that some of the video poker games at the bars were pretty worn down.The free covered self-parking is great, or use the valets if you don't want to lug your bags. There's an AM/PM mini market across the street for basic supplies, or a supermarket a short drive away. I never felt concerned about my safety. The Trop's location is wonderful, with an easy walk to the big casinos or a bus stop right out front to catch the Deuce shuttle if you insist on not walking (but it may drive you mad to see how slow you'll move in a bus - or any vehicle - up and down the Strip). It's also an easy walk across the street to catch the Monorail at the MGM Grand, which will conveniently take you to the Sahara at the far north end of the Strip with several stops in between. We found the monorail to be a perfect way to cheaply and quickly get to a trade show at the Convention Center.We had a wonderful time at The Comedy Stop at the Trop. They had three great comics in an 80 minute show (the early show is nonsmoking, and the comedians change about every week or so). This was by far the best bargain we found for a show in Vegas, with a free drink each (get beer if you don't like cheap well booze), for less than $20 a ticket. Look through the magazines for coupons. We tipped the Maitre d' $5 and got a seat in the front row. We only wandered down through the &quot;mall&quot; kiosks toward the other tower once but must say that no one badgered us about time shares.I visit Vegas once or twice a year and for more upscale trips, I used to love some of the newer hotels on the Strip. But honestly, with that huge new City Center Beast being built, I wonder if it's worth the price to have that as your view? All in all, we would recommend the Tropicana for a nice budget stay on the Strip, if you keep an open mind and are willing pay more for -or charm your way to - an upgrade. I thought they'd be tearing her down soon but I must say, from our experience it seems like they're still trying to please, and I'm happy she's still standing. It's probably only a matter of time until she's replaced by some Megalometropolis with no soul. I'll take my Vegas old school while I still can.	
