Oct 24 2008	Pros and Cons	My wife and I stayed 3 nights at the Trop. and concluded it was what we expected after reading the reviews. The place has seen better days, but it has a great location and is a good value.Pros:1. It is in a great location with easy access either by walking or short tram ride to the MGM, Excalibur, NYNY, Luxor and Mandalay Bay.2. The price is good when compared to these other resorts3. The staff was generally helpful and upgraded us without a hassel.4. Good gambling (our friend hit for $3,000 on a slot) and its easy to get free drinks and accumulate comps.5. The food in the Italian and Japanese restaurants was very good.Cons:1. It is old and dilapidated in many parts--while I didn't notice any particullarly bad smells, there were plenty of stains and tears in the carpeting and a general run down atmosphere.2. The pool while large was largely shaded this time of year and there was no bar easily accessible--also the hot tubs were crowded and unappealing.3. The late-night (past 10:00PM) food options are limited to the Garden Cafe which has a limited menu and not very great atmosphere.4. The rooms (we saw three different ones) all had some flaws and each bathroom had mold on the tiles.5. The &quot;Trop Shops&quot; are nothing more than the cheap boutiques ytou would see in an average mall.My advice if you decide to stay here is to AVOID THE GARDEN ROOMS and if you have to stay in one make sure it has a balconey and overlooks the pool. Get a tower room--we were staying in the Paradise Tower, but I asked and they upgraded us to an Island Tower room with a mirror on the ceiling (not so big a deal). The first room we were given had a AC unit that didnt work and that had leaked water allover the carpet. I asked to change and they moved us up to the 19th floor and a much better room (top of the line in the 1970s!). I would recommend staying on the top floors if possible since it seemed the furnishing were better there.	
Oct 23 2008	We came to gamble	Date:10/23/08 My wife and I spent 5 days at the Trop and had a GREAT time. The place is not as glamorous as the surrounding properties but offers better gambling, service and hospitality than any other casino we've ever been to.When we arrived Jake checked our luggage asked where we were from and wished us Good Luck.Check-in was easy. They had our room ready and were friendly.The room wasn,t fancy but functional. Older bed and furniture but very clean.It more than served its purpose for the few hours we spent in it . No problems with the bathroom or climate control system.Housekeeping was on the ball. One day we hadn't left the room until 3 P.M. and a note was left in our door telling us that if we required cleaning on that day we could contact them. I ran into a housekeeping supervisor in thehall and she asked if we needed towels or toiletries.The casino areas were older in decor but clean with a fairly good variety of slots.The table games were awesome! First of all you can actually see. Its very well lit unlike other casinos where you have to squint to see your cards for the sake of decor. The dealers are the best in town that we've met . they,re friendly ,engaging and a lot more patient than I could be in certain situations. Nikki, Sammie,Algonesh,Benny,Iris,Frank and the majority of the dealers were a lot of fun and frequently had everyone at the tables converted from perfect strangers to new aquaintences with the common, friendly goal of beating the house . As far as pit supervision , Suzette and Ron were friendly and engaging but what was truly amazing was how Sung never stops smiling and laughing with customers and co workers dispite the hectic pace of the pit at times. Don't take my word for it. Ask the people sitting at your table that are staying at MGM ,NY,Excalibur,Luxoror Planet H-Wood why they're gambling here and not where they're staying. If video poker is your game go to Lucky's Bar in the east side of the casino. If you're playing a bar machine during the late shift and he's not swamped with orders, talk to Jerry the bartender to get a feel for what it's like to live in Vegas and maybe some things you didn't know about Vegas.Definitely one of my favorite barkeeps ever(and I know many).Three little known treasures at the Trop .Comedy Stop: Three great comedians nightly. Only $23 and that includes a drink. Short of a comped show I don't think you'll find a better bargain.Legends Steakhouse: Great food , great prices , dinners include salad and sides. 4 to5 star food and service at 2 to3 star prices. Cozy ,classy and friendly. Mizunos: Quiet and comfortable Japanese food prepared at the table.Delicious house drinks and great service.Bottom line: If you come to vegas to shop, get hot stone massages or sit in your room and watch TV go somewhere else because the Trop is the real deal for what Vegas was meant to be.	
Oct 22 2008 	cheap... but cheap for a reason	I've been going to Vegas for about 25 years and have liked the way many hotels have updated to the new, Palms-inspired look, with the flat screen tvs and modern decor. But like many others I wanted to save a little money, what with the economy headed to the toilet!I wanted to go to the first Barrett-Jackson Auto Auction but knew that the rates at all the top hotels were going to be high. After some shopping I saw that the Tropicana had a rate of $45, which beat the $70 at the NYNY and the $129 they wanted at all the nice places for a mid-week rate. What I missed was this $7.99 room fee (plus taxes) they add to your bill each day. In return I got an easy check in on Wed but who is checking in on a Wed? So there were no real problems in getting a room. It was way back in the Island Tower, which is a good 5-7 minute walk from the desk. There are only a few slot machines near the lobby there, so be prepared for a long walk if you forget something in the room. Elevators are plentiful and all but 2 are outside, glass elevators with cool views.The room is straight out of the 1970's, with tacky wood-framed mirrors over the outdated bed, an old tube-television and clock radio. It looked like the decor in a Days Inn! The bathroom layout wasn't much better, with thin, rough towels, a big round tub in the corner and a weak shower head that was only 5 feet high. Be prepared to stoop! I also noticed BLACK mold on most of the tile in the shower. The central AC was fine but I actually would have liked one a little noisier to cover the sounds of aircraft taking off! I was woken up at 7am and ended up having to stick my noise-canceling headphones from my iPod in my ears! Was also woken up by several ambulance sirens, which I've never had happen to me in Vegas before. The glass in the room needs to be thicker if it faces the airport, don't you think? Also, the drapes would not shut all the way, and let in too much light through the middle or the edges. I had to prop a couple of pillows against the drapes in order to have a dark room! Haven't had to do that in Vegas rooms in decades!The hotel is not impressive at all but like I said, I wanted to try to save some $$$. I went to the buffet for their $9.99 breakfast and it was a rip off. I didn't want to wait 5 minutes to get an omlette prepared so I tried the scrambled eggs, but I think they were fake! The only thing they did well was the french toast. I did like their pool area, but it gets little sun because half of it is blocked half the day.I'd say the parking was probably a high point, as you can enter right off a side street and there were plenty of spaces in the covered parking area. I expect that this hotel fills up on the weekend though, and wouldn't want to deal with a crowd on top of all the problems or low quality issues. The slot machines were loose, much looser than most places on the Strip, so if you hit a small jackpot I suggest cashing out and getting a good meal at one of the many places across the street!	
