Sep 13 2008 	Okay but would stay elsewhere	My wife and I stayed at the Tropicana from September 5th - 12th, 2008. We came down to attend the wedding of two of our friends and this is the hotel they booked. There were about 15 of us staying at the hotel. We rented a car at the airport, plugged in our Garmin and directions to the hotel were spot on. We were kind of unsure where to park though. You can park in the 'self park' lot. It's a big cage with the valet parking above. It's also covered which is a nice plus. Though even in the shade it was 96 degrees! It is a bit of a walk from the parking lot to the main entrance of the hotel but not unmanageable. With a few kids and suitcases etc. I can see how it could be an issue though. Checking in went smoothly though I thought we were staying in the Paradise Tower but were told we were booked for the Island Tower. We proceeded on our lengthy journey to the far side of the property, through the casino, down the hall of vendors past the pool and then finally arriving at the tower. Room was clean but and the bathroom was spacious. I laughed at the bamboo trimmed mirrors on the ceiling - right out of a Poison video or something from the 80's. We asked about a fridge earlier and within 15 minutes of arriving at the room there was a knock on the door and a brand new fridge was delivered and plugged in. We stayed two nights in this tower before paying an upgrade of $20/night to stay in the Paradise tower where the rest of the wedding party was. It was a much newer tower and the toilets were jet assist which scares the hell out of you every time you flush - especially after you forget about it. :) My one complaint was with ironing a brand new white shirt and it left iron deposits on the fabric. I took the shirt and the iron down to the manager and he was quick to get it drycleaned for the next day as well as order a new iron. A few hours passed and no iron. I called down and an iron was quickly delivered yet again very dirty steam holes. (At check out I was surprised to see the charge on the bill, but again he apologized and removed the charge). No big deal. I was just glad they took care of things like that. It was nice to see. The rooms are dated - yes. The smoke everywhere is just something one has to get used to I guess - it's Las Vegas. Though some of the nicer hotels have their casinos in separate rooms. Here you walk in the front doors and have blackjack tables dead center and you have to walk around to get to the front desk or the elevators. The carpets are in need of replacing too. But I hear they're planning on impoding the building in 2010 (I've heard). Then I hope they build a bigger and better Tropicana. The name has been around since 1957 when it was first built so it would be a nice 'rebirth'. There are lots of different machines to play as well as the normal tables. We found the penny machines to pay well without a big initial loss. Average win about $150. Lowest was $90 and highest was $280. The pool is amazing and I just wish we spent more time there but we decided 5 trips to the outlet mall was a better choice - haha. The waitresses near the pool repeating the phrase 'Cocktails, drrrrinnks' in a Southern accent grew old quickly. There were always lots of chairs and towels were given out freely without any hassle. We did buy our drinks at Target and Von's (same as Safeway and they accept your Safeway card/phone number) - juices, pop and beer/drinks. I guess we're just too cheap but it can get expensive buying them from the hotel at premium prices - especially when a 26 of rye at Von's is $12 and a case of beer - 18 cans is $13.The $8 charge for using the pool/weight room (never even noticed one there)/parking is a joke but hey, I knew about it going in. I just don't understand why they don't include it in their nightly rate.Hookers/ Drug dealers... yup. Right outside the front door as well as walking through the hallways/casino. Hard not to notice and it appears management doesn't mind them there. Whatever - they never bothered us except they love standing in your way.What else.... rooms were clean and maids did a good job. I think they came in 4 of the 7 nights as we don't need daily service. My wife calls me paranoid. The safe in the closet was nice and worked for all but the last night. You can enter your own number or use a credit card - why would you use a credit card?? Just seems like another way of identity theft waiting to happen. (Yup... more paranoia)If you're looking for a cheap meal, the Garden Cafe inside the restaurant is the place to go. $5.99 specials and they're HUGE. The chicken caesar salad is almost comparable in taste to anything offered back at home and is only $5.99. Anyway... all in all it was a good experience though I wouldn't stay there again when so many other hotels have better amenities for the same price. We're all planning on going back to watch it crumble into little bits of concrete, paint and dust.	
