Jun 11 2008 	Hellhole.	As a travel agent that specializes in no-frills budget travel, I thought I'd give the Tropicana a chance on a trip to Vegas this month. They aren't the cheapest place on the Strip-- plenty of hotels have cheaper rooms, a lot of them recently updated. But... The Trop's a classic, so we gave it a shot. When we got to the hotel, it was about 11:00 am. I knew that check in wasn't *technically* until 3:00 pm, but we were checking in on a weekday the week AFTER Memorial Day, so the chances that EVERY room was completely full were slim to, uh, NONE.Walking in the hotel lobby and casino, we were overcome by the smell of smoke and sweat and dust. The place is old, there's no getting around that, and they are in desperate need of an overhaul-- especially with their HVAC systems! I walked up to the desk and we were gruffly told that we had to go outside and leave our bags will the bellhop and that we couldn't check in until after 3:00. Fine. Didn't have to be so rude, and there wasn't any reason for them NOT to check us in, but whatever...We checked our bags, got lunch, and then did some wandering around. We headed back to the hotel at about 4:30 to get checked in and to clean up and change before dinner. The line, for check in, went down into the casino it was so long. We waited for an hour and a half just to get checked in-- completely unacceptable! They could have been checking people in slowly, as rooms came available, instead of requiring everyone to come and wait at the same time. And if that is the method they're going to use, then they need to staff up to accomodate everyone.When I got up to the desk, I was told that we were recieving a complimentary upgrade to a &quot;tower&quot; room since I was a travel agent. Sweet! ...At least that's what I thought until we got INTO the room... The beds were sagging and gross. I don't even want to THINK about what the mattresses looked like underneath the dated and tattered bedding.The carpets were old, stained, and literally coming up off of the floor. They were all bunched up in places and ripped in corners and along the walls.The bathroom, while a nice size, was DISGUSTING. The shower was falling out of the wall, the tile had a decade's worth of mold on it, the fan/ventilation didn't work, the toilet was cracked, the floors had someone else's hair on them, and the shower curtain was filthy and falling off of the rod-- half of the hooks weren't even attached! The room stank of cigarette smoke and mildew and the air conditioner didn't work at all. (And the windows didn't open, so there was no respite from the dank air!) Instead of pumping in nice, cool air, the A/C pumped in recycled cigarette smoke and stale casino air at stagnant temperatures-- and we were in a &quot;non-smoking&quot; room!The decor was what I expected. Dated. Tacky. The television was just a small, dial television sitting on top of a rickety old dresser. There were a few ugly, faded &quot;paintings&quot; on the wall. The wallpaper and paint was coming off in places. The curtains were old and dusty. At night, we noticed that the curtains were full of moth holes and little beams of light shot through the &quot;black out&quot; courtains and into our room. We slept one night in the room. When I woke up in the morning, my throat was scratchy, my eyes burned, and my chest was congested-- and I don't even have allergies! We got ready and went down to the buffet for breakfast. I'm not a big breakfast fan, and I don't want a lot from a breakfast buffet, but sweet baby Jesus, the buffet was TERRIBLE. Even though it was mostly empty, we were made to wait in line after line. The buffet was over $10.00 and it consisted of a few random settings of food-- and NONE of it of any quality! The waitstaff were exceedingly rude, the food kept disappearing, and there were NO labels above any of the items to help you identify what, exactly, the slop in the tray was. I even witnessed a buffet employee yell at and push a buffet customer. For what? Dripping a little sauce on the buffet line. That afternoon, I'd had my fill of the Tropicana. I went to the desk and told them that not only had my experience been unfortunate, it had been absolutely unacceptable-- I've stayed in third world country hostels that were nicer than the Tropicana! The clerk didn't even want to hear my whole story-- there were three people behind me in line saying the same thing, and it seemed like the poor guy spent the majority of his day swapping rooms for pissed off guests.They switched our room to the OTHER tower, which was much nicer. Not NICE, mind you, just nicER. It was more along the lines of what I expected-- a hotel can be old, dated, and a little tacky but still be CLEAN. The new room was clean, well-maintained, and had a nice layout. It was still a standard room, not a suite, but it was the type of room I would have expected for my $50-$80 a night. Problem? They sell these rooms for over $100 a night-- so not worth it! You can stay at MUCH nicer hotels, in better Strip locations-- for the same price!After my first room, I was terrified to think of what my original room would have been like... If that room was my complimentary &quot;upgrade,&quot; what is a &quot;basic&quot; room at the Trop?!I am not a high-maintenance traveler. I don't require the nicest ammenities, the newest technology. I know that you get what you pay for, and I'm fine with a dial television and a few tacky paintings. But whether one star or five, there is NO excuse for the disgusting condition that the Tropicana is in right now.My suggestion? Take your money somewhere else. Shoot, take it across the street to the Excalabur-- they just remodeled and their prices are even cheaper than the Trop's!	
