n one like this. I did not get the satisfaction that I should have received from a service related industry that the hotel represents. This hotel used to be the &quot;Gold Standard&quot; for Las Vegas, but now it is an embassment. This was my wife's first time to the area and most likely the last one thanks to the treatment we received.	
May 28 2008 	Cheap Rooms Not Worth The Savings	I was in town for a convention at the MGM. To save money for the company, we opted to stay a the Tropicana across the street. The hotel rooms in the cheapest tier ($69 on my stay) are very large, but they are in serious need of renovation. The 20 inch TV was on a rolling cart. The bathroom had stains and tiles falling off the wall. wall plugs are few and far between. On the last night of my stay, the handle on the sink broke. Luckily, I knew I could cut the water off from under the sink or otherwise I would have had to get the staff out pronto at 4AM to fix the problem.The casino its self is also dated. There were no video blackjack machines and the video poker had poor payouts. I did not spend much time at the Tropicana other than to crash after a full day at the convention. If I had intended on spending more time there, a $20 a night upgrade may have been worth the cost. If you do book this hotel, avoid the cheapest rooms at all costs.The location on the strip is ideal. A cab ride will cost you about $14 each way to and from the airport. Once there, you can walk to many other casinos or catch a cab to other strip locations. I would bet that the Tropicana will be replaced with some other casino in the next few years similar to what happened to the Sands and other Vegas institutions.	
