May 21 2008 	Go someplace else unless your standards are very low	How can you say awful? This hotel in its day was a true gem of the southern most part of the Las Vegas Blvd 'Strip'. Today, it's a bankrupt shadow of its former self.The rooms are priced very low, compared to other Strip hotels, and there's a reason why-- the place has been allowed to decay to a dump. The staff seem to be trying to assuage the pain, but it's a losing battle.The property has seen better days. While I was there, perplexing maintenance issues plagued the place. Elevators were shut off. A primary down escalator, one that's needed to get to both towers in the facility, wasn't working the entire time; handicap accessibility in the hotel is poor. You get charged a room fee of something like $7.95 if you book through an online source like I did (the hotel website might be different), allowing you to do things like use the pool and health center. Not that anyone checked. Add on top of that, $13.95 a day for weak WiFi whose sign-up system won't let you book several days worth if you need it (I did), and you must renew inconveniently, every day, where the site doesn't remember you. Want food? Have visions of inexpensive Las Vegas buffets or coffee shop food? Not at this hotel. Like to walk? Good, as you're a quarter mile from the front door to anywhere on the Strip. Fortunately, I like a good walk. The walk will be by various vendors in the main corridors, some of whom are quite aggressive.Perhaps if the room didn't have cigarette burns through it like a freeway no-tell-motel, and the shower/tub combo was useful, it might have been a bit more pleasant. My 'room with a view' (of the pool) might have been nicer if the windows had been washed sometime in the past decade. Perhaps it's better not to have a view of the pool area, itself very strange. There are numerous pools, none of which has any of the elan of other Strip hotel pools. They don't seem to be heated, and if it's chilly out, the wind whips through the place, blowing any and all things away. Perhaps wind generators are appropriate here, to heat the pool. The swim-up bar was closed. A couple of decades ago, it was a cool place to be. No more.If you're not from the US and want to see what's probably the way Las Vegas was in the 60's and 70's, this is it, gaudy, baudy, and now well past its prime. Should your standards and budget be really low, this is your place. You can do better elsewhere. Maybe anywhere.	
