Mar 10 2008 	If the price is right stay if not look elsewhere	After reading previous reviews here I had some serious trepidations about booking a 3-night stay at the Tropicana. In the end the $66/night for an Island Tower room was too good to pass up. The room is not terribly spectacular, the other user submitted photos are a fair representation. My room was on the 8th floor with a fabulous view of the airport. The room was just high up enough to not be bothered by the noise of the HVAC equipment on the roof below. The room was a typical king bed room, with two rather smallish nightstands, a small desk/dresser combo, full-sized sofa bed with coffee table, a pair of armchairs, and a 19&quot; TV with very few channels. Oh and let's not forget the mirrors... mirrors behind the bed, above the bed, and beside the bed. It is great if you like watching yourself sleep or you enjoy basking in classic Vegas tackiness. The bed itself was ok. The mattress was newer and in good condition, but slightly hard for my tastes. The linens and bedding are typical cheapo hotel fare and is one place where they could have done much better, especially given that cost conscious chains like Holiday Inn Express, Hampton Inn, etc have really put together nice bedding packages lately. The first night there were a measly 3 pillows on the bed, however the maid kindly gave us 2 more for the remaining nights.The bathroom is rather large with a roomy vanity with a large mirror. Island tower rooms get a soaking tub. The actual property is an interesting mix of old and new. The casino is rather small and cramped looking. And you have to wind your way through it to get to the Island tower. The pools are the Tropicana's strong suit, you are not going to find a better pool setup for the money on the strip. Sure there are places with nicer pools, but not for &lt;$75. Unfortunately the main pool and the indoor pool were being resurfaced during my stay. It was not until I was headed to checkout on the final day did I actually notice the heated outdoor pool was open. The dining options were rather limited. I sampled the breakfast buffet my first morning and came away rather disappointed. Sure it is cheap at $9.99 but the variety is pretty limited, the service slightly below average, and the quality was marginal. You could get a better breakfast at a Waffle House or Denny's. On the plus side you cannot beat the location. Within walking distance of the MGM Grand, New York New York, Excalibur, Luxor, Mandalay Bay, Showcase Mall, etc.... And then there is the Duece, right out the front door on the strip. Overall the Tropicana is a decent value as long as you are just there to sleep. Go elsewhere to eat and to have fun. I doubt I will stay there again, especially given some attractive rates some of the nicer hotels on the strip offer.	
Mar 5 2008	Mirror mirror...	I booked an Island Tower room for one night at $52.00. I received room 360 in that Tower. The Island Wing was very long and tiresome walk far away from the front desk. And the elevators were slow and only appeared to have 1 out of 5 running. I always had the same elevator and it was always packed to the brim full of people.The room itself was adequate for my needs with a King bed, Non-smoking. No view to speak of except for part of Hooters and the HVAC equipment on the roof below. I actually really liked the tacky Island theme of the room with the fake bamboo on all the furniture and the ugly drapes and bedspread. But I didn't understand the need for all the mirrors on, above, and around the bed. Perhaps it would be fun if I were video taping an adult movie with sexy, athletic bodies, but I didn't enjoy seeing myself in all these different angles.My favorite part about the room was the bathtub. It is deep and perfect for soaking. That makes up for the long walk through the casino, across the river and through the pool to get to the room. Soaking in that big tub at the end of the day was wonderful.Overall, the price was great so I shouldn't complain. I would stay here again but would pay the $20 different to be in the Paradise Tower that is near the front of the propeerty.	
Mar 2 2008 	Great location but a tired hotel	I stayed for 7 nights with my husband, we found the whole vegas experience a very surreal one. However having travelled over 20 hours to get there you can imagine we had some pretty severe jet lag, so unlike many people in Vegas we spent quite a bit of time in our room.Similar to most, we were offered an upgrade for $10 a night which we declined at first, but the garden room we were allocated was awful, overlooking an air conditioning unit, not the garden, broken furniture, just genrally shabby, so we had to trapse back to check in and upgrade to the island tower (check in took us nearly an hour altogether as we had to queue again!). This island tower room on the 11th floor was clean, the maid came every day and we had amazing views of the strip. It wasn't noisey and we found the room service was prompt and pretty tastey.We found the Tropicana's decor very dated and the esculator from the casino floor to the tower lifts was broken. The child like drawings of parrots on the lifts did amuse us, but using the lifts always made you feel sick because the outside windows looked like they had never been cleaned, which when you whizz past makes it look like its raining and made me dizzy!The pool was amazing and well worth a day by, sipping 'football' sized cocktails. The Foiles Bergere was worth it too, and we got BOGOF tickets for being residents. We enjoyed the Japanese restaurant out of all the restaurants there, but we tended to find other places to eat, breakfast at the Mandalay Bay was awesome, pasta by the casino in the Venetian was a joy and sausage and mash in the Irish bar at NYNY was also brilliant (inluded some live music, felt like home!).All in all the Tropicana is a tired hotel with an awesome location and brilliant value for money. There was talk while we were there that it will be pulled down and replaced by the usual mega resort which in a way is quite sad. If we ever went back to Vegas we'd stay downtown, probably in the Golden Nugget (I like my swimming pools and their's is amazing).I guess if you have no expectations of a polished hotel then like us you will have a pleasant enough stay!Word of warning, don't use the tours desk in the hotel, it's not run by them and had some of the most expensive trips to the Canyon we ever came across!	
