Jan 16 2008	Good base for a holiday in Las Vegas	I stayed at the Tropicana for a couple of nights in 2000, so I knew it wasn’t the fanciest or most up-to-date of the Strip hotels, but I was quite nervous having read some of the reviews on here. However, my husband (who had been to Vegas more recently) reassured me it wasn’t that bad.And it wasn’t. We stayed in the Island Tower in a room on the sixth floor. While the room was a little dated, it was clean and comfortable and had everything we needed. I'd stay there again.Positives* It’s in a great location on the Strip, within easy walking distance of all the other casino resorts. Compared to the prices of other Strip hotels, it’s a bargain, too.* The room was clean, comfortable, huge, use of the safe was free (I hate having to pay extra to use the room safe!) – all in all, an ideal base.* Staff were friendly and helpful. * The eat-all-you-can-for-a-set-price breakfast buffet was good. Strange to see apple pie offered at breakfast but hey, my husband enjoyed it!* Maybe a slightly strange one … but I really like the casino floor ceiling!Negatives* The room wasn’t cleaned until the afternoon – in fact one day, it wasn’t cleaned until after 5pm. It would have been nice to have it made up earlier.* The charging structure is so opaque! Why oh why isn’t there a flat rate per night, instead of a room rate, and then a resort charge (what is this supposed to cover?), and then tax?* I would have loved a kettle, cups, and tea and coffee in the room. These are pretty much standard in the UK and I’m used to being able to make a cuppa when I wake up without waiting before going down to breakfast.* The idea of an indoor pool appealed to me, but when I went to have a look at it, I was really disappointed. It felt like it was in somebody’s garage – it was all concrete-y and not at all inviting.* The &quot;Trop shops&quot; are a bit tacky (but then, this is Vegas!)One thing that really surprised me is that smoking is allowed in casinos. Thinking about it, I can understand why it’s allowed from the point of view of the casino owners, but as a non-smoker, it’s a really annoying feature of a holiday in Las Vegas.	
Jan 14 2008 	Good location Nice Hotel for the price	I found this hotel was pefect for us, we got a good rate of $65 a night, great location, and we even got upgraded to a Paradise Tower room at no extra cost because we checked in really late, was sold out. Was on the 21st floor, great view facing MGM Grand. We ate breakfast and dinner all over the place, but even the restaurants at the Trop were pretty good, and decent price.What I must remind everyone, you're paying under $99 a night or less, don't expect the Wynn or Venetian! This is basically a hotel that is in a great location on the strip, and is pretty damn cheap, but by no means a dump... I've stayed at way worse places than the Trop. The rooms were clean, quiet, had a in-room safe, the A/C worked great, had a fridge in our room (I think they cost $10 per night but ours had a fridge anyways so we didn't pay extra), only problem with our room was the TV was poor reception but who cares, we basically get a room to sleep and shower, and thats it, I didn't travel to Vegas to hang out in my hotel room. We had friends who were in the Island Tower rooms and it seemed ok as well, actually I think it was a bit larger than ours, and had a larger bathtub, and mirrors above the bed etc... not bad at all. The Garden rooms we did not even see, so can't comment on those.The casino was pretty good for us, I didn't care too much about the high roller tables like at the Wynn or Bellagio, I felt right at home playing at the Tropicana, the atmosphere is a bit more quieter, the drink service was good, and they had a few $5 tables open all day long, probably the only casino on the strip offereing $5 blackjack. The casino is a pretty good size... however the Pokerroom is quite small and only had 2 maybe 3 tables going at a time, sometimes just one, but the buy-ins were cheap and good action there, the dealers are nice and they make you feel comfortable for any beginners that are playing. We played both limit and no limit games, I think min buy in was $50 or so? The worst part of the Casino would be the Sportsbook, if you even find it! It's hidden somewhere and they still use the old boards, nothing is electronic, a few tv's and maybe 2 tellers... very small! I guess its kind of neat to see how things were back in the day when they used dry erase markers to change the odds, lol.The hotel pool was really nice, very large (we were there in August when it was +110, very HOT! The pool was busy but not packed with kids, was perfect. Also did some gambling at the swim up blackjack table, kinda neat.The restaurants were decent, your typical buffet, nothing special but wasn't bad at all... the other restaurant was a sit down, more upscale, we had a steak/crab legs dinner and was excellent.We also checked out the Comedy Stop, hilarious stand up comedians, and the Dirk Arthur Magic Show, really good show (not quite as good as Lance Burton).Overall, I was satisfied with the Tropicana, I knew I was staying a low budget hotel compared to the bigger hotels down the strip. We choosed Trop over Imperial Palace and glad we did. The location is great, a walkway to the Excalibur, NYNY and MGM, plus the monorail can take you to Mandalay Bay, Luxor in a few minutes. Would stay there again for sure....	
