Jan 10 2008 	Dated and ripe for replacement	I stayed here during the CES show in January 08 and booked it because it was the cheapest thing on the strip with a decent location. The rest of the big-name hotels were more than $500 a night, so I picked the Trop for $180 a night to cut costs for my business. Unfortunately, I was not impressed with the Tropicana and felt like it had not been updated in any way since the late 70s or early 80s. The casino and hallway to the Island Tower were old, dark, full of smoke, and had music from the 50s and 60s playing (I presume that's when this hotel was popular), had worn carpet. Elevator lobby was hard to find for the Island Tower and was tacky and grungy. The rooms were no different than what you would get from a Motel 6 (exception: larger bathroom). TV was small and had only a handful of channels. Windows were filthy. Beds were hard. The rooms were clean though, to the Trop's credit. The $5.99 &quot;resort&quot; fee is a crock- you get absolutely nothing for it. There isn't even a health club that I could find.Overall, this place had such a dated and old-time feel to it that it was out of place sitting next to the MGM Grand, across from New York New York, Luxor, and even Excalibur. Time to implode it and build something new, because nobody obviously cares about updating it.	
