Jul 1 2007 	Needs upgrading but good location and clean rooms	We stayed at The Tropicana for just two nights and it was okay but not great. Upon arrival, it was difficult to find reception, and I was frustrated at having to drag my heavy suitcases up two short flights of stairs and get them through the heavy glass doors. Then on our way to the elevators, we had to go through a huge group of people singing karoake and dancing. It was uncomfortable.The room was clean and air conditioned, and we appreciated the in-room safe to put our valuables. The bed was very hard and I had a terrible sleep both nights. The door sometimes just didn't close, and our sink was plugged, but the very nice housekeeper had it fixed for us right away, so that was good.We stayed on a Saturday night and the price was ridiculous, but Sunday night was a reasonable $50 or so. The hotel is dated and needs a lot of upgrades, but it's in a good location to other more expensive hotels and casinos on the strip (we didn't even have a drink at The Tropicana). I doubt I would stay here again, as on our way home after a 10-day roadtrip, we stayed at the Sahara for $43 and it was better all around.	
Jun 30 2007 	The next one to be torn down...	Let me preface this review by saying that we were in a comp room...That said, the hotel looks like it's in bad shape, and I predict it will be the next major property to be torn down. It's location is great - right on the strip, across from New York New York, Excalibur, and MGM. I don't have much nice to say about the hotel though - the halls smelled funny, the carpet is in terrible shape, the elevators are slow, and the ceilings are very low. But - the rooms were big.I predict that this will be down down in the next 10 years to make room for something worth going to. There really isn't much of a chance that the Tropicana can be &quot;revitalized&quot; - there are too many problems, and the structure doesn't lend itself to a successful remodel. Don't waste your time here, unless you can get in free like we did! It is worth staying in, if you can do it for free!	
Jun 29 2007 	OK Under Limited Conditions	I have been to Vegas many times but this stay was prompted by a flight cancellation. I wanted to stay in the least expensive reputable hotel closest to the airport and that turned out to be The Trop.I was using Hotwire so I didn't know which property it was until after I booked or I would probably have chosen a different hotel. The Trop is old but clean. The pool area is lovely and restful. The decor in the rooms is outdated but the rooms are large in the Towers. My check-in also required an extremely long wait even though there were 5 people working the front desk (around 5pm on a weekday). But there were other times when I passed through the lobby and there was no wait at all. The staff was friendly and helpful. My lower rating is primarily because (a) I asked for a nonsmoking room and was placed on a smoking floor, and (b) the 3-star rating (3.5 star rating on Hotwire) is deceiving. This property was a 3-star hotel 30 years ago . . . and it hasn't been updated since. So you feel like you are in a 1-star hotel that's just extremely large.All the hotels allow smoking in the casinos and other places. So, if smoke is problem for you be sure to request a nonsmoking room on a nonsmoking floor. Eat outside of the hotel; the food at the Trop was not terrible but nothing I had in the restaurants tasted fresh or flavorful. Food in Vegas is very competitive and usually great, so you can walk over to any of the other nearby properties and have better meals for the same price or less.If this is your first trip to Vegas I strongly suggest you stay somewhere else because this property will not give you the wow experience you will have at just about any other hotel on the strip. After you walk up and down the Strip and see other properties you will be depressed when you return to the Trop. Another low-budget option that has better food, service and entertainment is the Imperial Garden. Or check the reviews for The Flamingo. Both are in the middle of the busiest part of the Strip and give you more options. Or spend a little more and stay in one of the newer theme hotels.	
Jun 28 2007 	Very Dated	Upon arrival there was a 45 minute que to check in and had to carry the luggage up 2 sets of stairs just to get into reception. The hotel is very dated, there is a 5 minute walk through a very tacky casino to get to the lifts to your rooms. Had a buffet breakfast which was awful, except from the very happy man behind the counter making eggs! Much rather spend another 2 dollars to have the breakfast buffet at the bellagio. The room was fairly clean, but the shower head was hanging out of the wall, one thing that is good, room had amazing view of the strip. Stayed here for 1 night after staying at the Bellagio for 3 nights, maybe this is why the hotel looked so bad, or maybe its because it is bad! Much better hotels on the strip then this, stay here if your on a budget and wont be in the hotel for anything else then sleep.	
Jun 27 2007	Stay Away from the Parking Lot view rooms	My wife and I stayed at the Tropicana for two nights in the middle part of June. Normally, we would not have thought to stay here but last year when we stayed at the Mandalay Bay, while walking around, my wife and I were enticed to join the Tropicana Winner's Club by a couple of free magic show tickets. Since then we have received promotional materials from time to time with low room rates at the Tropicana . The two nights cost $39 and $49 with an additional $5 &quot;resort&quot; fee and taxes. The Tropicana opened in the late 1950s and it seemed that our room in the 4000 wing must have been part of the original structure. For a 50+ year old building it wasn't in bad shape but it was definitely more like a roadside motel than a &quot;resort&quot;. The rooms were clean enough but not spic-n-span clean. The grout on the tile in the bathroom was black and moldy underneath the sink and the carpets were well worn. The towels too were clean enough but not super clean and had no plushness at all. As far as the service, the physical state of the facilities is also indicative of the staff attitude during our stay, we probably came across at least twenty different employees of the hotel, but only one offered a smile or a greeting. This should be covered in basic training for hospitality but don't expect it here.The biggest issue we had though was on our first night, right below our window facing the parking lot a car alarm went off at around 2:30 am. We called the front desk and were told they were working on it. The alarm continued to sound until finally at 4:30 am, we gave up on trying to sleep and had our room changed. We were upgraded without cost to the much newer, cleaner, and quieter Paradise Tower. Also, we asked for and received free meals at the breakfast buffet. The upgraded room and free meal was nice but I question how hard the management worked to get the car alarm turned off. According to the management, they can't have the car towed, can't break in and unhook the car battery, they can't call the license bureau and find out who the owner of the car is and find out what room the owner is in, they can't put a big sound absorbing tarp on the car, they can't go door to door and ask each guest what kind of car they have. What can the management do? I guess all they can do is change rooms for the guests who complain. Some good things about the hotel, although the pool closes at 7:00 pm, it is large and has a couple of waterfalls to swim under. There were plenty of chairs and the waitress could be counted on to come by every so often to get us drinks. The exercise room was included in the &quot;resort&quot; fee. It was nice with five pieces of aerobic equipment, free weights, and several strength training machines. Also, there was access to a sauna. The location of the hotel is also very good. It was easy to walk across to the MGM Grand or to catch the tram to head further up the strip. An all day tram ticket cost $8. Overall, considering how much we spent, the value was good. Despite some problems, we would probably stay again but only if we can get a courtyard view and not the parking lot.	
