Jun 20 2007	Cheap...yes. Worth the savings...no.	There is really only 2 reason to think about staying at the tropicana...location and price. The tropicana is in a nice spot on the strip with easy access to a number of other hotels (MGM, NYNY, Excalibur, etc.) and has the lowest rates for the area (~$50 on a weeknight).That being said, that is about all there is to like about the tropicana. On our 6 day trip we decided to stay a 3 nights somewhere nicer on the north strip (The Mirage) and then 2 nights to save money at the Tropicana on the south strip.Upon arriving at the Topicana after 3 days at the Mirage, our initial impression was negative. After leaving the car with the valet we moved to the bell desk (in case we couldnt check in yet), which at the time had too many bags and therefore had bags sitting on the sidewalk at the hotel entrance. This is not exactly my idea of a secure area to store our bags.Next was an attempt #1 to check-in. It was 2:00 and there were people sitting all over the lobby waiting for their party to get through the checkin line. After a few minutes it became obvious why. The checkin desk only had 3 people working and the line was moving at a crawl pace. The line was so long and not moving at all that we decided to walk our bags with the man at the bell desk by hand into the back room to store our bags.We returned for check-in attempt #2 at ~4:30 and were very unhappy to see the SAME SIZE LINE. Since we had to get into our room and wanted to get to the pool we waited in the line for an hour before being helped. I used the $20 trick and got an upgrade to the paradise tower rooms.The room itself wasn't bad for the price we paid and we had a strip view which was pretty nice.Our next stop was the pool which a lot of reviews talked up as being great. I definately have to disagree here. Was the pool a decent size? Yes. Was the pool enjoyable? No. Basically it felt like being at a trashy spring-break pool with guys smoking cigars in the pool, ashes floating by, dirty water, etc. Also, the towels at the pool are more like hand towels and even 2 of them didnt cover the out-of-date chairs. The swim-up blackjack is in a covered area at the side of the pool and the whole blackjack/bar area felt dirty.We also tested out the Garden Cafe for breakfast one morning and it again was below par even for the low prices. The service was unpleasant, style old, and food was below average.Overall, if deciding whether to stay at the Trop or to spend $50 more to stay somewhere a little nicer (which there are a number of hotels), I would definately say take the extra cost and save yourself the dissapointment.	
