Jun 11 2007 	Run down hotel good location	We visit Las Vegas every year and make it a point to stay at a new hotel each time. The Tropicana was advertising great rates and the location is good, so we decided to give it a try. I was able to get the rate reduced twice prior to arrival, first to match an Expedia rate and again the day before check-in to match their own e-mail rates. This is one of the most inexpensive hotels on the strip.Check-in took a while but the clerk was very friendly and accommodating. We got a room in Island Tower, which is better than the Garden rooms but not as nice as the Paradise Tower. On the other hand, the Island Tower is the closest to the pool. The room was a decent size, but run down. The furniture was very worn, and the bathroom was in desperate need of remodeling. The toilet never stopped running during our 5 night stay. There were mirrors above and beside the bed.The pool is very nice, but not adequately maintained. There was stuff floating in the pool every day. One day there was disgusting scum floating on the adult pool. I hate to think what it was. The pool area itself is quite nice.The only food we sampled was the deli, which was OK. The buffet was recently rated one of the 10 worst in Las Vegas, so we stayed away. With the great selection of restaurants in Vegas, there is no need to settle. The casino was OK but nothing special. They have discontinued the acrobat acts that used to perform in the casino from time to time. That is a shame since it really added to some to an otherwise bland casino.We got comped to the Folies Bergere, a classic Vegas show. It was OK for the price (free). The Comedy Stop is a real gem. $20 per person including a drink, and $5 coupons are readily available. We go there every year and have never been disappointed. Great talent and a cozy room make for the best bargain in town.The Tropicana is not a place for someone on their first trip to Vegas. but for an experienced traveler looking for cheap digs in a good location this is not a bad place.	
