Apr 26 2007 	It's old...But at least it's on the Strip	I just recently stayed at the Tropicana in Las Vegas for a business conference. Here is what I thought about the Trop.Service:I found that the service was pretty good. Everyone from the staff at the restaraunts, the dealers, gift shops, and maid staff were very friendly. We gambled a little bit at the Trop and all of the dealers were always friendly and the cocktail service was friendly also. It wasn’t as bad as people were saying I thought.Check in:The check in lines were extremely long! They had about three staff members checking guests in but the line lasted about 20 minutes long. As we were walking around other hotels along the strip at similar times when we checked in, I thought that other hotels were better staffed to help guests check in.Rooms: I stayed in the Paradise Tower which was the tower in the front of the hotel/casino. This tower which I have heard from other tripadvisors was the better of the two. The rooms were ok. Each hallway appeared to have different wallpaper and furniture. I stayed on the 21st floor which was nice and gave us a great view. I know that you don’t go to vegas for the view but it always helps. It was a better view that one of my colleagues had of McCarran Airport. In the room contained the following:TV and night stand which had limited space for clothing. (I just lived out of my garment bag for the week.) It had an alarm clock, small empty fridge to store drinks in, not 1 but 2 safes which I thought was odd (which you had to insert your credit card in and pay to use them which was a first for me!) A small closet, iron and ironing board, and shower toiletries such as shampoo, conditioner, and soap. There was also a table with two chairs and on demand movies through the television set. The beds were clean and surprisingly comfortable. The decor in the Paradise Tower (at least on our floor) was old victorian. The bathroom was clean but can tell had not been updated in quite some time. There was no mold, bugs, or anything like that in my room but looked like a bathroom that you would find at someone’s grandmother’s house. I went and visited colleagues who stayed in the Island Tower and saw the famous mirrors on the ceiling. Put it this way, three weeks after the trip, those mirrors are still a running joke amongst us! Casino:The casino was spacious and nice. It was not a casino where you would get lost in unlike some others on the strip but had your basic games to choose from. It also had a variety of different types of slots and other video poker games to choose from. There was a very big area of penny and nickle machines so if that is up your alley, a stop by the Trop wouldnt be bad. The table limits were very manageable and at night, there was a good amount of people at the tables. The casino is right next to the front entrance and elevators to the paradise tower so it can get a bit crowded. The dealers were very nice and the cocktail waitresses were nice also with surprisingly quick service. Also, the bars located in the casino were very liberal if you had coupons for free drinks. If coupons were valid at one bar, you could use them at the other bar. They were very accomodating about this. There is also a poker room and sports book but I did not visit them during this trip.Entertainment:We went and saw the Comedy Show and Folies Bergie at the Tropicana. For $20 bucks, the Comedy Stop at the Trop was well worth it. The show lasted about 1 ½ hours and included a free premium drink. There were three acts and one I remember seeing on Comedy Central. It was well worth it. Arrive early for a good seat. Folies Bergie was your classic Vegas Show. There are not too many shows left like this but me and my group enjoyed it. There are two different shows. The early show is the family show and is not topless while the later show is topless and for adults only. Also, the showgirls can be seen walking around the casino floor during the day. They are very friendly. If you plan on seeing the show, try to find discount coupons as you can get two for one tickets. ($75 for two people is not bad!)Dining:The dining at the Tropicana is ok. It was nothing spectacular. We ate mostly outside the hotel while we stayed at the Trop. The two places that we did eat were at Mizunos Japanese Steakhouse and The Garden Café. The Garden Café is open 24 hours and serves your basic light fare. It is reasonably priced but nothing to go out of your way for. It is more of a convenience eatery. Miuzuno’s is your typical hibachi steakhouse. As the food may be pricey, I was surprised by the portions. Usually when you go to a hibachi restaraunt, the portions are small. At Mizuno’s, the plate was full of food and I was stuffed. $$$$ though.All in all, the best thing about the Trop is the location. It is on the corner next to MGM, NY NY, Excalibur, Luxor, and Mandalay Bay. We spent most of our time in the Excalibur and NY NY. The Trop is old and I heard that they are suppose to renovate again. It’s not like filthy dirty but just old. It’s not brathtaking like walking into the MGM, Luxor, Bellago, TI, etc. If your on a budget, then this is the hotel for you. Even though people say you don’t spend a lot of time in your room, you usually spend a lot of time in the hotel you are staying in though. Even though I had a great time with the people I was with, I would stay somewhere else.	
Apr 26 2007 	My home away from home	I recently stayed at the Tropicana Hotel in Las Vegas on April 3rd and 4th, 2007. I have stayed there several times. It is one of my favorite Vegas hotels. I like their tropical ambiance. As usual, there were no real problems with my stay there. The staff is always courteous and friendly. The Tropicana is one of the original hotels in Vegas, but their rooms are still nice and comfortable. The Trop still has one of the nicest pool areas in town. It is nicely landscaped, with waterfalls and lagoons, and palm trees. They claim to have the only swim-up blackjack table in town. Their wedding chapel is also located in the pool area, which is rather nice. The 24-hr coffee shop has views of the pool area. It is a very pleasant atmosphere in which to have breakfast, lunch, or dinner. The Trop has some fine restaurants on site. The new Legends steakhouse is intimate and has excellent food. The Trop has one of the most attractive casinos in town with stained-glass canopies over the table games (but who ever notices the decor while gambling). However, the rest of the casino looks just like any other for the most part. Best of all about the Tropicana is its location. It's right on the corner with some of the biggest mega-resorts in town, the MGM Grand, New York New York, Excalibur, Luxor, and also close is Mandalay Bay. All are within easy walking distance by way of escalator and walkways. Another good thing about the Trop is that the rates are usually more reasonable than other hotels (around $59.00 per night). The Tropicana may soon be destined to be either renovated or most likely demolished to make way for something new, as it is being considered to soon be under new ownership. Until then, the Trop will continue to be my &quot;home away from home&quot;.	
Apr 25 2007 	Horrible stay at the Tropicana Resort and Hotel	For a weekend getaway to Las Vegas with some college roommates, we booked our room at the Tropicana through hotels.com based, in part, on a 3-star rating. The hotel itself is old, dirty, dingy, smoky - with a number of unhappy / unfriendly / unhelpful employees who work there (not all were like that, but there were quite a few!).Our room was decorated in vintage 1970s Florida-themed furniture, drapes and spreads that appeared not to have been updated or cleaned in the 3 decades since they were new. There were really bad stains on the sad excuse for a couch. Thecarpet was filthy. The beds were small, the mattresses were lumpy and uncomfortable, and the sheets, pillows andblankets were old and worn. This is not what we expected for a room costing more than $200 per night. We have stayed at newer/nicer motels for $75 a night. We thought the room was bad, until we saw the bathroom; remarkably it was even worse than the rest of the room: broken light fixture. Wallpaper hanging off the walls. Mold and mildew stains. Broken flush handle. The hinges around the toilet seat were filthy. Chipped formica countertop. Crusty plumbing features. Towels that were thin, coarse, and stained. Seriously - we didn't know whether to laugh or cry. The indoor pool and spa were similarly lacking in luxury, charm, taste or comfort. When we went to use the hot tub, we found both a smoker and a child in diapers enjoying it..... After seeing our room and accepting our fate, we did appreciate the (expired, but still accepted) coupon for a free cocktail at the &quot;Lucky&quot; bar. Our drinks were served in cheap plastic cups, and when we asked for salted rims on our margaritas, the bartender depressed us even more by telling us about his high blood pressure problems!! Beyond the features and amenities, the most appalling thingabout our room was the &quot;smokiness&quot; of our alleged non-smoking room - they put a wing of &quot;no smoking&quot; rooms right down the hall from the casino - and didn't enforce the smoking ban in the non-smoking areas of the hotel (there clearly were people smoking in some of the rooms that we passed by to get to our room). During the night, we all woke up coughing and had to place towels against the door to try to keep the smoke from coming in. We spent our entire weekend with congestion, eye irritation and sore throats from the smoke exposure in our &quot;no smoking room&quot;. Last but not least was the front desk staff, some of whom seemed to have the &quot;like it or leave it&quot; attitude. We tried to change rooms Saturday morning after a miserable night Friday. The front desk told us they would get us another room by 1 pm. We waited around until 1 pm (taking time away from sightseeing). At 1pm, they told us to call back in 45 minutes. Then at 1:45 they said 3. Having already wasted the better part of the day, we went out for a few hours. When we returned to thehotel, we were very rudely told that they had released our room and we were out of luck. We tried to speak with the manager on duty on our way out Saturday evening, and she told us that she couldn't do anything or give us any credit against the bill because we had booked through hotels.com. Although the experience has since provided us with some laughter after-the-fact, it's actually hard to believe that this is what travelers who book a non-smoking room in a 3-star hotel for $225/night have to face - and seem to have no recourse; not even an apology. We e-mailed them via their website and never received a response. We didn't expect a room at the Ritz, but certainly didn't expect this!My advice: given the lack of care with which they maintain the hotel, I would strongly suggest staying elsewhere if you're visiting Las Vegas.	
