Mar 3 2007 	The way Vegas was meant to be!!	My two young children and I had a wonderful stay at the Tropicana, Feb 26/27, 2007. I had been researching this trip and was a little put off by all the negative reviews so I decided to avoid the Garden level rooms and spend a little extra to book the island Tower. The price differential is not huge, and the room was perfectly nice and clean. It was admittedly not updated as far as decor but then again, that was not important to us. The windows opened for fresh air, which meant far more than updated furnishings in a newer hotel with windows that don't open! Bathroom was clean and spacious, beds comfortable. Besides I loved the 1970s tropical/wicker ambience. I love the whole 1970s Love Boat atmosphere - you almost expect to see Captain Stubing appear! If you don't care for it, then you probably won't be happy here. The Island Tower rooms either offer a view of the Strip, towards NYNY and MGM, or of the airport with the mountains in the background. I seriously enjoy this about Vegas, waking up to the view of mountains in the morning. We went down to Java Java to get coffee for me and juice/bagels for the kids, took it back to our rooms where the kids watched their favorite TV shows and I gazed at the mountains. Then we explored the Trop's lushly landscaped grounds and I really felt that this was &quot;The way Vegas was meant to be!&quot; We spent the afternoon at the pool and hot tub, which was very relaxing. The abundance of shops and dining options meant that we did not have to leave the entire day, which might sound odd for a Vegas trip but made for a very relaxing getaway. The historian in me could visualize the glamour of times past, of movie and TV stars long dead who might have enjoyed this property in their heydey, and it gave me a sense of possibility and connectednessthat I have not felt in some time. Admittedly not in 20 or so years! I have stayed in more &quot;modern&quot; properties and was less than charmed by their higher price tags for sleeker design but less character. It's all in what you are looking for. For me, yes, this was a truly wonderful stay, and I have a definite favorite hotel in LV for future trips.	
Feb 28 2007 	Won't go back	Stayed with friends weekend of 2/23/07. I had stayed before a couple years ago and thought it was rundown, but perfectly acceptable for the price. As long as a hotel is clean-ish I can deal with it. This trip was not good. The bathroom was dirty - hair on floor. We had a room with a small balcony and there was a glass with soda (?) on one of the chairs, filled with cigarette butts for the entire weekend. The hallway to our room was smelly and dirty. Our neighbor's door had crushed crackers in front of it for the entire weekend. Our thermostat did not work and at one point was 80 degrees in the room. When I called down to the front desk to complain/have it fixed, no one answered. My friend kept turning the unmarked fan switch until she got it to turn off the heat. The fan/light in the bathroom is connected and the fan is for noisemaking purposes only as the bathroom was always filled with steam. The hotel staff I spoke to were actually pretty nice -- esp. the front desk and bartenders and black jack dealers. But in the lounge act bar the &quot;waitress&quot; would only bus the tables, not take drink orders, then rush over to flirt with the bartender. Next time will stay at the Flamingo for an extra 20 or 30/night.	
Feb 27 2007	Great for young couples on a budget!	After reading some of the bad reviews on here, I was nervous to stay here....Don't listen to them! If you are a budget traveler, this hotel is great. However, I don't reccommend this hotel for people used to &quot;fancy&quot; hotels, or those who mind a short walk. If you want to stay at the Bellagio, don't stay here and also, don't stay in the Garden Rooms-they look tacky. Great location, it has walkways to Excalibur (which has a tram to Luxor and Mandalay Bay) and MGM, and it is right across from NYNY. Just got back from a long weekend at the Tropicana. I'm 25 and went with my boyfriend, we are on a budget and would much rather splurge our money on shows, gambling, and drinking than a fancy hotel room. We were able to check in at 12:30, the line looked long, but moved fast (besides, you wait in lines everywhere in vegas). We stayed in the Island Tower (we had a great view of the New York New York), and we had a nice, clean, quiet, comfortable room with a nice-sized bathroom and the two of us could fit in the tub. The non-smoking room did not smell like smoke, the bed was comfy and had bamboo-lined mirrors above the bed and on the wall near the bed-as a young couple, we loved it and it is not as tacky as it sounds. The Island Tower is a short walk from the casino, but it's nothing compared to the walking done in Vegas. Sure, the casino was smokey...but NEWSFLASH-Every casino is smoky. We didn't try the buffet, but we did try the one at MGM and it was okay, the buffet at Treasure Island was outstanding.Tips:See a Cirque Du Soleil show-Mystere was awesome.Take the Duece Bus up and down the strip, $5 for 24 hour pass.Visit the Ellis Island Casino and restaurant.-Our cheapest meal by far and we each won big in the casino!	
Feb 26 2007	seen much worse. right price !	Stayed for 3 nights from Feb 10-13. My first night was in the &quot;garden area&quot;. NOW how is that nobody has mentioned that the GARDEN area has no AIR CONDITIONING in the winter months! We had to leave the patio door open to keep cool but the outside noise kept us awake.So if you like it cool stay away from the garden area in the winter.We were then moved to the Island town very avg. room no complaints.The all the time $5.00 black jack is a bonus for this hotel.The island buffet is not bad. But they do not offer toast for breakfast.the check in staff was very friendly and helpfull. If you are going to vegas and Tropicana hotel tell the taxi driver not to take the tunnell and to take Tropicana blvd.I arrived 5 hrs. before my grandfather and it cost me $11.00. It cost my grandfather $22.00.	
Feb 23 2007	Cheap price = cheaper room	The tropicana hotel &amp; casino in las vegas is very old...and it definately shows in both the rooms and rest of casino/hotel areas... The rate was VERY cheap so we decided to try it out because we wanted to stay at that end of the strip and you really arent in your room that much after all.... Our room was kinda dirty... Dirty windows (inside &amp; out), the bathroom floor had hair on it, the shower was filthy and after we had them clean it and we used it for the first time, the drain was clogged... The ceiling in the bathroom dripped from time to time in one area (i guess from the room above us)... We complained and got a free night out of them... If your looking for a &quot;NICE&quot; room dont stay here... They need to renovate or just demolish and start over.	
Feb 22 2007 	Never Again for the Tropicana	We had stayed there one night last year and kept getting offers so we decided to take them up on one. We stayed in Mid February for 3 nights. I will not be back.The room was spacious but worn down.The carpet was stained and thread bare, the grout and flooring in the shower/toilet area was discolored with rust? Mold? The AC was not very efficient, the Refrigerator did not cool at all, one of the bathroom sinks was missing the part that lifts the plug, the brass (?) was not shiney it was discolored and dull, the TV's were little for such a large room, there was very little &quot;Drawer&quot; space, the bamboo was pretty tacky and uncomfortable, the vent in the toilet room was on the same switch as the light so it sounded like a 747 in the room with you and it smelled of stale smoke even though I requested Non Smoking. The wal to the Island Tower was very long and it was a scary walk late in the wee hours of the morning. The Good: It was large, had a nice view and it had a jacuzzi (The jacuzzi was nice but you had to be a monkey to climb in and out of it).The mirrors were bordering on creepy...they were everywhere.This property needs a face lift in the worst way.**If you care about this sort of thing the dealers were rude and unprofessional..I only stayed with some because I was winning**	
Feb 21 2007	Never again. What a dump!	Stayed at the Trop during the CES show due to the fact that most of Las Vegas was sold out already. All I can say about the Tropicana is: What a dump! The bathroom was not only kinda dirty if you are over 5 ft 5 in tall you are sure to hit your head on the showerhead…repeatedly. The rest of the room was very, very tired. On the plus side the size of the room was nice. Another negative is the hallway to get there was smelly and beat up. There was a small news stand selling soda and water on the first floor next to the elevator which was nice. The check-in person wasn’t really helpful and the check out person was worse. Got dinged for $11 per day for some sort of resort fee (pools, gym etc.) which is a total rip off and should be illegal to run such a scam. Unless you currently live, or vacation in a cave and are used to dirty substandardliving conditions steer clear of the Tropicana.	
Feb 20 2007 	There's a reason this place is priced so low...	This place stinks -- literally. We had two &quot;garden area&quot; rooms (aka ground level, near the rear exits). In order to walk to our rooms, we had to travel down endless, twisting hallways and corridors, some of which smelled like raw sewage. The hallways and rooms also had a mildew / stale cigarettes smell to them. The carpet was thin and cheap. The bedspreads/comforters were thin and cheap. The towels were thin and cheap. You get the picture...On the plus side, you're right in the middle of the &quot;Strip&quot; (aka Las Vegas Blvd.), and for a decent price. You can walk or take a cab to anywhere you need to be.	
Feb 2 2007	We were disgusted and will never return.	I booked two rooms for three nights at the Tropicana where we stayed for my daughter's 21st birthday. I last stayed at the Tropicana in 1999 and I had some good memories. However, the hotel has very much gone downhill since, along with some questionable practices. The first thing that happened is that the cost of the first nights for each room was deducted from my debit card at online reservation time, wihtout notice. Never seen this before.The rooms were dated, the shower did not work, there was no shampoo/soap or conditioner on arrival night, and very few towels. The HVAC system was loud and barely functioned. (This is for the Paradise Tower, supposedly the best). The bed was so hard that we barely slept, got up with back and neck pain on day 2, which nearly ruined the rest of the trip. We tried to play the slots for a while and eventually became nauseous from the heat and a lack of ventilation combined with heavy smoke and rancid smell. My daughter waited over two hours for a complimentary soda. On night three, we asked customer service if we could borrow two glasses to finish our bottle of champagne (had to finish before flying back, could not pack bottle) and were told that would cost us $6.00 + $4.00 delivery fee -- even if my husband went downstairs to get it. Now this is to BORROW the glasses! Same with borrowing a corkscrew ($5.75). This is a place where we had spent in excess of $800 between 2 rooms, gaming, bars, valet etc. Again, never seen this before. We were completely disgusted and will never return, probably not even after the place is &quot;renovated.&quot;	
Jan 28 2007	Well Worth It If You Know What To Ask For	First of all, the Tropicana is in an excellent location on the Strip. It's right beside the MGM and within seconds of the Luxor and Excalibur. Lets face it that's right in the heart of things. Now for the rooms, the regular rooms in my opinion are dirty and shabby and I would avoid booking. I would however recommend the rooms in the Towers. I have stayed in both and the Tower rooms are bigger, cleaner, more secure and quieter.Also the benefit of being up high is the view. I found the casino to be quite good and there was always somewhere to eat day or night. At one stage I also was sure that there was more free drinks on the game floor than most other Casino's. This may have changed though. You will get cheap rates in this hotel if you shop around and if you get a tower room I'm sure you will be happy.	
Jan 16 2007 	No problem with the Tropicana	I just returned from a week's stay at the Tropicana. I went there to attend the Consumer Electronics Show. That show was expected to draw almost 150,000 people. Needless to say, the town was nearly sold out and room prices reflected it. After reading a number of reviews on this site, I decided to stay in the Paradise Tower portion of the resort.. Most of the complaints about rooms tended to come from those who stayed in the Garden Area of the hotel. These are the cheapest rooms (by about $30) and also the oldest, as they are part of the original resort. Their room rates were quite modest by comparison to most other hotels.The room I was given was a bit dated but was surprisingly large, clean, well supplied and everything was in working order including ample hot water. The room was quiet, bed comfortable and the ventilation system worked just great. I was on the 16th floor and had a great view of the Strip. Check in was efficient and the staff was pleasant. I never experienced problems with staff anywhere in the hotel. In fact, I and my business partner had a number of meals at the Garden Cafe and the waitress we had for breakfast each day always seemd to find some way to tease and joke with us. I had read on this site that the Tropicana was going to close after Jan. 1, '07 and be torn completely down and something else put up in its place. I thought that would be a shame, as I've always found the Trop. to be a good value for the money charged and a pleasant place to stay.I talked to several staff while I was there and it seems that the above description was the original plan. However, the original development company has sold out to another development comnay and the current plans call for them to tear down the original, 3 story (Garden Area) section of the hotel while keeping the exiasting towers and casino in operation. They will then build three new towers and, when they finish, the Tropicana will be a 10,000 room hotel, the largest hotel in Vegas! It is likely that the hotel portion will be operated by Marriott or Westin and those two chains are the ones that the new development company works with most often.So, for those who found the Tropicana to be such a terrible experience - give it a few years and try again. You may find a whole new Tropicana to like!!	
